{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The practice of depleting the forest for precious fuel during hard times has been taking a toll at taps in the capital city, Lilongwe....", "abstract": "Rampant deforestation of Dzalanyama Forest Reserve in Malawi for illegal production of charcoal has lead to unprecedented level of environmental degradation in country; forest is catchment basin for Lilongwe River and destruction of trees has significantly cut forest's ability to retain and release water in rainy season; charcoal production, along with regional drought, is contributing to drastic shortage of water in capital city of Lilongwe.", "section_name": "World", "print_page": "5", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Norimitsu", "role": "reported", "lastname": "ONISHI", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By NORIMITSU ONISHI", "contributor": "Raphael Mweninguwe contributed reporting."}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/21/world/africa/poverty-drought-malawi-water-supply.html", "lead_paragraph": "The practice of depleting the forest for precious fuel during hard times has been taking a toll at taps in the capital city, Lilongwe.", "headline": {"main": "Poverty, Drought and Felled Trees Imperil Malawi Water Supply", "print_headline": "Drought and Felled Trees Take a Toll at Malawi\u2019s Taps"}, "_id": "57b8868495d0e021d7981baf", "word_count": "1228", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/08/21/world/21malawi1/21malawi1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/08/21/world/21malawi1/21malawi1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 401, "url": "images/2016/08/21/world/21malawi1/21malawi1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/08/21/world/21malawi1/21malawi1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "401"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/08/21/